<h1> Shiner perch</h>



<Br></Br>


<img alt="" style="width:550;" src ="https://bloximages.chicago2.vip.townnews.com/theworldlink.com/content/tncms/assets/v3/editorial/e/42/e424a537-8967-5e65-ad9a-34c23bf820f5/597a59f37c934.image.jpg"</img>



<h4> Description: Shiner perch are silver in colour, with up to eight longitudinal dark stripes from head to tail. These stripes are often intercepted by three broad yellow bands. Their body is deep, compressed and protected with relatively large scales. Fins are usually colourless. Three spines are located at the anal fin. The caudal fin (tail) tends to have a fleshy colour at times. Maximum body length is around 20cm. </h4>


<h4> where to fish: Shiner perch can be caught almost anywhere along the shoreline during summer months. Look for small jetties, rocky shoreline, and heavily weeded area. Schools can often be spotted if they are present on a sunny day. In late summer, shiner perch are plentiful in the estuary Fraser River. </h4>


<h4> Fishing season: Shiner perch start to show in early september to early october in the tidal fraser river </h4>














